	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Commodity fund investment raises issue of functioning of cocoa supply chain</h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>ICTSD has posted an article noting the high price of cocoa and the activities of a London-based commodities fund, Armajaro, which ‘recently bought future contracts worth £650 million – an amount equivalent to 7% of all the cocoa grown in the world this year’. NGOs have expressed concern over this high level of speculative purchases, which it is felt, could limit the ability of farmers to benefit from high prices. It notes that international agreements such as those that govern cocoa are ‘powerless to cushion the fluctuations that often accompany commodities at peak prices’.</p><p>Cocoa prices have fluctuated widely since the late 1970s, an issue of considerable concern to the ACP, where many poor countries are involved in the cocoa trade (Côte d’Ivoire, Sierra Leone, Togo and Madagascar) and where in the case of Ghana it accounts for up to 34% of total exports. According to the senior statistician of the International Cocoa Organisation, Ghanaian cocoa farmers have not benefited from recent price surges, although this is attributed to ‘the limited liberalisation of Ghanaian cocoa market’. According to ICTSD, the cocoa price in Ghana for farmers is fixed at the beginning of the season, which insulates farmers from price declines but also ‘limits their ability to profit when prices shoot up’. Pressure is now mounting in the Ghana Cocoa Board to pay a bonus ‘as compensation for higher world prices’.</p><p>A debate is now taking place on how to make the cocoa market work better for farmers, with a critical issue being to identify ‘what policy tools are needed to ensure that farmers benefit more directly’ from the functioning of world cocoa markets.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ICTSD, ‘For cocoa farmers, high prices are bittersweet’, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest, </i>Vol. 14, No. 27, 21 July 2010 </p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/81244/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/81244/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The continuation this year of high cocoa prices comes as a relief to exporters of the crop, even if the price remains volatile, and in US dollar terms has not returned to the peaks seen in December 2009 and January 2010. Prices on both the London and New York markets have slipped back sharply since Armajaro’s coup<i> </i>in July.</p><p>Higher prices on international exchanges do not necessarily translate into higher earnings for farmers and farmworkers in ACP countries. This is particularly the case in a semi-industrial sector dominated by the chocolate industry. Within the EU, the European Commission is currently seeking to address issues of the distribution of value along agricultural supply chains, where inequalities in market power are felt to pose a threat to the underlying production base. However, at the moment the EC has no plans to extend its emerging policy on improving the functioning of agricultural supply chains to the international level. This being noted, the European Commission has shown a greater sensitivity to the issue of abuse of market power by dominant players in supply chains and appears open to the adoption of new regulatory initiatives, where this is warranted. A cautious approach is however being adopted. In this context an EC policy initiative to explore the scope for extending its emerging policy on the functioning of agricultural supply chains to the international level could offer a way forward. Cocoa would appear to be an obvious case for the piloting of a joint ACP-EU policy discussion on how to improve the functioning of global supply chains. This could build upon discussions and initiatives which are already in train in the context of the 2012 International Cocoa Agreement (see <i>Agritrade</i> article of August 2010, ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Commodities/Cocoa-sector/News" target="_self">New International Cocoa Agreement prioritises small farmers and fair pri...</a>).</p>
		</div>
		
